Preface

For this week problem set we will use WiFi localization data (the one we worked with on week 2) to fit logistic regression model and evaluate performance of LDA, QDA and KNN classifiers. As we have seen earlier this dataset should allow to locate phones fairly well by relying on the strength of WiFi signal, so we should expect to see fairly low error rates for our classifiers. Lets see whether some of those classifiers perform better than others on this data.

Important note: For the purposes of all problems in this week problem set, we will be predicting whether the phone is at location=3 or not, as opposed to working with multi-class predictor. In other words, before you proceed with any of the problems in this assignment, please convert the four-levels outcome to the outcome with only two levels: location=3 (must be 500 of those) and not (must be 1500 of them).

If you are creating a new column containing this binary outcome, please make sure that the original outcome with four columns is NOT used inadvertently as one of the predictors. If you are getting invariably 100% accuracy regardless of the choice of the method or split of the data into training and test, chances are your code is using original four-levels outcome as a predictor.

Compare them to the corresponding results from LDA, QDA and logistic regression. Describe results of this comparison and discuss whether it is surprising to see low training error for KNN classifier with \(k=1\).

k = 1 results in 100% accuracy, sensitivty, and specificity with 0 false positives or negatives. This is expected with k = 1, because it only considers the 1 closest neighbor to the data point. k = 5 still results in very high accuracy, sensitivity, and specificity all of which are 99%. This is closer to the QDA accuracy of 97% and 99% specificity, but the knn sensitivity is much higher. k = 25 results in 98% accuracy, sensitivity, and specificity, and 2% training error. As k increases, the number of false positives and negatives increases. For each k value tested, the knn accuracy, specificity, and sensitivity is higher than that of the logistic, LDA, and QDA results.

Problem 4 (30 points): compare test errors of logistic regression, LDA, QDA and KNN

Using resampling approach of your choice (e.g.cross-validation, bootstrap, etc.) obtain test error as well as sensitivity and specificity for each of these methods (logistic regression, LDA, QDA, KNN with \(k=1,7,55,351\)). Present results in the form of boxplots, compare test error/sensitivity/specificity across these methods and discuss their relative performance.

#logistic regression
logftn = function(data, index){
  logm = glm(V8 ~ ., data, family = 'binomial', subset = index)
  p = predict(logm, type = 'response')
  p = ifelse(p > 0.5, "1", "0")
  outcome = as.factor(data$V8) 
  p = as.factor(p)
  conf = confusionMatrix(p, outcome)
  results = c(conf$overall[1],conf$byClass[1:2])
  return(results)
}

logboot = boot(data, logftn, R = 1000)
#LDA
ldaftn = function(data, index){
  ldam = lda(data$V8 ~ ., data, subset = index)
  ldap = predict(ldam, type = 'response')

  conf = confusionMatrix(ldap$class, outcome)
  results = c(conf$overall[1],conf$byClass[1:2])
  return(results)
}

ldaboot = boot(data, ldaftn, R = 1000)
#QDA
qdaftn = function(data, index){
  qdam = qda(data$V8 ~ ., data, subset = index)
  qdap = predict(qdam, type = 'response')

  conf = confusionMatrix(qdap$class, outcome)
  results = c(conf$overall[1],conf$byClass[1:2])
  return(results)
}

qdaboot = boot(data, qdaftn, R = 1000)
#KNN with $k=1,7,55,351$)
for (k in c(1, 7, 55, 351)){
  knnftn = function(data, index){
    data = data[index,]
    knn = knn.cv(data, k = k, cl = data$V8)
    conf = confusionMatrix(knn, outcome)
    results = c(conf$overall[1],conf$byClass[1:2])
    return(results)
  }

  knnboot = boot(data, knnftn, R = 1000)
  
  err = paste('KNN error (k = ', k, ')')
  sen = paste('KNN sensitivity (k = ', k, ')')
  spec = paste('KNN specificity (k = ', k, ')')

  par(mfrow = c(1,3))
  boxplot(1 - knnboot$t[,1], main = err)
  boxplot(knnboot$t[,2], main = sen)
  boxplot(knnboot$t[,3], main = spec)
}

#boxplots
names = c('logres', 'LDA', 'QDA')
errplot = data.frame((1 - logboot$t[,1]), 1 - ldaboot$t[,1], 1 - qdaboot$t[,1] )
sensplot = data.frame(logboot$t[,2], ldaboot$t[,2], qdaboot$t[,2])
specplot = data.frame(logboot$t[,3], ldaboot$t[,3], qdaboot$t[,3])

par(mfrow = c(1,3))
boxplot(errplot, names = names , main = 'bootstrap testing error')
boxplot(sensplot, names = names , main = 'bootstrap sensitivity')
boxplot(specplot, names = names , main = 'bootstrap specificity')

Using bootstrapping, KNN shows the highest testing error with a mean between 0.37 and 0.39 for each k value. QDA shows the next highest error at approximately 0.36. Logistic regression and LDA show similar results with error around 0.32; however, logistic regression resulted in more outliers with higher error. The same trend in performance is seen with sensitivity, with the lowest seen KNN, followed by QDA, and similar results between logistic regression and LDA, which both have about 0.85 sensitivity. KNN show specificity between 0.25 and 0.28. QDA shows specificity around 0.23, with a few higher outliers. LDA and logistic regression both show mean specificity around 0.15, with more higher outliers for LDA. The specificities are significantly lower than shown above, without bootstrapping.

Extra 5 points problem: naive Bayes classifier

Fit naive Bayes classifier (see lecture slides for examples of using naiveBayes function from package e1071) to the WiFi localization dataset with binary (location=3 or not) outcome and assess its performance on test data by resampling along with logistic regression, LDA, QDA and KNN in the Problem 4 above.

nbftn = function(data, index){
  nbm = naiveBayes(data$V8 ~ ., data, subset = index)
  nbp = predict(nbm, newdata = data)

  conf = confusionMatrix(nbp, outcome)
  results = c(conf$overall[1],conf$byClass[1:2])
  return(results)

}
nbboot = boot(data, nbftn, R = 1000)

par(mfrow = c(1,3))
boxplot(1 - nbboot$t[,1], main = 'naive Bayes error')
boxplot(nbboot$t[,2], main = 'naive Bayes sensitivity')
boxplot(nbboot$t[,3], main = 'naive Bayes specificity')

Naive Bayes shows much higher sensitivity and specificity and very low error compared to the bootstrapped methods above.
